body:
The following code crashes the compiler:

``` rust
pub trait Test {
  fn something(&self) -> i32;
}

#[derive(Copy)]
pub struct Foo {
  field: i32
}

#[derive(Copy)]
pub struct Foo2 {
  field: i32
}

impl Test for Foo {
  #[no_mangle]
  fn something(&self) -> i32 {
    self.field
  }
}

impl Test for Foo2 {
  #[no_mangle]
  fn something(&self) -> i32 {
    self.field
  }
}
```

This compiles:

``` rust
pub trait Test {
  fn something(&self) -> i32;
}

#[derive(Copy)]
pub struct Foo {
  field: i32
}

impl Test for Foo {
  #[no_mangle]
  fn something(&self) -> i32 {
    self.field
  }
}
```

It seems that `no_mangle` encodes _nothing_ inside the function-name, not even the type it was implemented for in the end. Implementing 2 of them leads to a conflict.

This should either not be allowed or not lead to an ICE.

Error:

```
vagrant@precise64:~/ice-test$ RUST_BACKTRACE=1 rustc --crate-type=dylib ice-test.rs
rustc: /home/vagrant/src/rust/src/llvm/include/llvm/Support/Casting.h:237: typename llvm::cast_retty<X, Y*>::ret_type llvm::cast(Y*) [with X = llvm::Function; Y = llvm::Value; typename llvm::cast_retty<X, Y*>::ret_type = llvm::Function*]: Assertion `isa<X>(Val) && "cast<Ty>() argument of incompatible type!"' failed.
Aborted
```
